<DOC><DOCNO> AP880908-0258 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 0232EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-InsiderTrading-Glance     09-08 0216</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Insider Trading-Glance,0221</SECOND><HEAD>With PM-Insider Trading-Drexel Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here is a summary of Wednesday's developments inthe federal investigation of insider trading:   _The Securities and Exchange Commission filed civil insidertrading and stock manipulation charges against the investment firmDrexel Burnham Lambert Inc. and Michael Milken, the head of itsjunk bond trading unit. Gary Lynch, the SEC's director ofenforcement, said the allegations involved 18 series oftransactions, including 16 involving Ivan Boesky, the former stockspeculator now in prison.   _Stephen Sui-Kuan Wang Jr., a former junior analyst at theinvestment firm Morgan Stanley andamp; Co., pleaded guilty in to thefirst criminal charges stemming from what the government has calledWall Street's second largest insider trading case. Wang is said tohave stolen market-sensitive information about pending takeoversand sold it to a Taiwanese businessman, Fred C. Lee, who thegovernment alleges used the information to make at least $19million on stock trades.   _William Dillon, a former Merrill Lynch andamp; Co. stockbroker,pleaded guilty to a second count of wire fraud after admitting hehad traded stock based on the contents of an investment column inundistributed copies of Business Week magazine. Dillon was thefirst person to face criminal charges as a result of the BusinessWeek investigation. </TEXT></DOC>